you ever think about how good su was for having a big grand space opera narrative but framed as the family secrets a bunch of over protective parents weren't telling the child protagonist in an otherwise slow slice of life story

my two other favorite shows farscape and steven universe do this too, but in SU the family's outsider status is kept hidden from the child protagonist and it's about him discovering it. farscape is more front and center about it, so in a weird way i'd compare it more to farscape
and even within that fully realized world, the characters constantly question that world building because our ragtag family of protagonists are perceived as criminals in their society
it uses the lax expectation of the cartoon medium to satirize and pick apart contemporary fantasy tropes and at the same time build up its own complex world full of distinct settings and characters

So anyway.  I would argue that Owl House is as radical as SU was in its heyday but not for the gay stuff and that it is not for the gay stuff that got it cancelled.

3 Big Themes I got from my TOH rewatch:
-People, but especially disabled people, do not need to prove utility to justify existence
-Be critical of the school to army/police pipeline
-False scarcity created in the name of "civilization triumphing over savages" is actively harmful

Eda never wanted to compete with her sister, she wanted to learn more than the limited track of study the system offered her. It failed Eda and made her an enemy (monstrous both ideologically and physically) in the same blow.
And it all ties together in a plot thread that I can only call "Hey, let's be critical of the high school to army/police recruitment pipeline."

Love how it whiplashes between "School bullies are so mean :( Who will you take to the dance???" and "The government makes public only the corporal punishment of chosen figureheads like Eda, but inflicts the punishments on other witches out of the public eye."

Love the dramatic tonal shift of the end of Owl House S1.  It's light hearted self aware teen witch high school misadventures all the way through then suddenly it's "No music. Witches are getting carted away. Lillith walks through the castle halls in silence. Catholic vibes only"
The overarching theme is that you should not have to prove your utility to justify your existence, and imo, I think that more than the gay stuff, is why the mouse canned it after S3

It is an issue of mental health, as such keeping it a secret does no good to anybody.  But it also overlaps with anxieties of not being able to comply to mainstream beauty standards but the way I see it: If I never shave then all the other hair makes up for the lack on my head

As such, I can say "Do I want to stop or do I want to continue?" and make a conscious choice about it. Doesn't always work but *shrugs*.  Also the moment I openly started talking about it was the moment I stopped worrying if people can see bald spots. If they know they know

My experience is not the same as others, as all our experiences are different. Trich was/is a symptom of my anxiety and once I figured that out it stopped being something I worried about. I still do it, less frequently, and can identify why I'm doing it when it happens.
Everytime I post about trich I get likes and follows from various organizations or causes who think that is what I will always post about.

There's a handful of things that didn't age well, usually in easily skippable fillers, but nothing that detracts too much from the core values and overall story.
It's bombastic and joyful and oddly life affirming for something so incredibly steeped in the heteronormativity of 1999-2004 mainstream television.

Personally I had a very fun time.  It is full of beautiful characters who have fantastic arcs and journeys and big bold ideas. It's also about a family. It's also about how alien bodies work. It's also about puppets. It's also about the protag going bonkers.
Final thoughts on Farscape: Colorful, kinky, chaotic. Whether you will like this show and what you will get from it will vary individual by individual.
